# Propose a draft review for a GitHub PR

**Inputs**:
- The PR record (from `detect-prs.prompt`), including `cycle_count`.
- `cycle_count` (integer ≥ 1) — passed in by the orchestrator and
  used to locate the current cycle's upstream artefacts and to
  shape the draft's tone (see "Cycle-aware tone" below).
- The triage verdict at
  `../output-github-prs/pr-<N>/cycle-<C>/triage.md`.
- The analysis at
  `../output-github-prs/pr-<N>/cycle-<C>/analyze.md` (the source
  of all findings the draft will surface).
- When `cycle_count > 1`, the prior cycle's review at
  `../output-github-prs/pr-<N>/cycle-<C-1>/review.md` — the draft
  must acknowledge it (and the author's reply or new commits)
  without restating it verbatim.
- The PR's `meta.md` at `../output-github-prs/pr-<N>/meta.md` —
  gives the current comments / review timeline; useful when the
  draft needs to reference what the author said in their last
  reply.
- The full project tree (`../context/`, `../output/`,
  `../output-analysis/`, `../README.md`, `../CLAUDE.md`,
  `../.project/`) — used to anchor citations in the draft.

**Output**: `../output-github-prs/pr-<N>/cycle-<C>/review.md`.
Plain markdown, ready to paste into `gh pr comment --body-file`
OR `gh pr review --comment --body-file` (routing decided below).

**Skip if**:
`../output-github-prs/pr-<N>/cycle-<C>/review.md` exists AND its
mtime is newer than the triage file's mtime AND newer than the
analysis file's mtime. If any upstream artefact moved, the review
is stale and must be rewritten. A new cycle folder is always empty
when first created, so this skip naturally applies only when the
same cycle is being re-run.

**Execution mode**: invoked for every PR that reached this stage.
The anti-loop cap (D5, `cycle_count >= 4`) is enforced upstream by
`detect-prs` — by the time this prompt runs, the cycle index is
guaranteed to be in `{1, 2, 3}`.

---

## Verdict (D11)

Pick exactly one of:

- **`LGTM`** — no blockers, no suggestions OR only `info`
  findings. The PR is clean.
- **`SUGGESTIONS`** — at least one `suggestion` finding, but no
  `blocker` findings. The PR can merge; the suggestions are
  quality nudges.
- **`BLOCKERS`** — at least one `blocker` finding. The PR should
  NOT merge as-is. The review states the blockers explicitly with
  reasoning grounded in the analysis.
- **`SCOPE-MISMATCH`** — at least one `blocker` finding on the
  scope axis AND the body / diff disagree on **what** the PR is
  (not just on whether every change is mentioned). This is a
  special-case of `BLOCKERS` that gets its own verdict because the
  remediation is structural (split the PR, retitle, rewrite the
  body) rather than fix-a-line.

When both `BLOCKERS` and `SCOPE-MISMATCH` apply, prefer
`SCOPE-MISMATCH` — the scope issue is the dominant signal and the
remediation cascades.

## Mergeable decision (D11)

Orthogonal to the four-way verdict above, every review MUST end
with a **binary conclusion** about whether the PR is ready for the
maintainer to merge:

- **`MERGEABLE`** (`mergeable: true`) — the PR is a good addition
  and can land as-is from the AI review pass's standpoint.
- **`NEEDS-WORK`** (`mergeable: false`) — the PR needs changes
  before merge.

The verdict (`LGTM` / `SUGGESTIONS` / `BLOCKERS` / `SCOPE-MISMATCH`)
characterises **what the review found**; the mergeable conclusion
characterises **what the author should do next**. They are
orthogonal because a `SUGGESTIONS` verdict can still be NEEDS-WORK
(e.g. open points TBD declared by the author remain unresolved),
and a clean `LGTM` is almost always MERGEABLE.

### Decision rules

Set `mergeable: true` when **ALL** of the following hold:

1. `verdict ∈ {LGTM, SUGGESTIONS}` (no blockers, no scope mismatch).
2. **No open points TBD** declared by the author remain unresolved.
   Open points are findings raised by `analyze-pr` in Axis 1 with
   the flag `blocks_merge: true` (TBDs, "open questions",
   "deferred", "to-be-decided" markers in the PR body, in
   `context/` files diffed, in `.project/decisions/`, in PROJECT.md
   threads).
3. **No unverifiable load-bearing claims** — every substantive
   claim in the PR has evidence grounded in `context/` or, when
   the D6 keyword detector tripped, in NotebookLM. A claim tagged
   `[inferred]` on an axis-1 finding with severity ≥ suggestion is
   a blocker for mergeable.
4. **No broken cross-references** — the convention axis (Axis 2)
   confirms internal cross-refs introduced or modified by the PR
   resolve correctly. A finding pointing at a broken cross-ref
   blocks mergeable regardless of its severity.

Set `mergeable: false` when **ANY** of:

- `verdict ∈ {BLOCKERS, SCOPE-MISMATCH}`.
- At least one open point TBD remains unresolved (axis 1 finding
  with `blocks_merge: true`).
- At least one load-bearing claim cannot be verified without more
  info from the author.
- At least one internal cross-reference introduced or modified by
  the PR is broken.

When a `BLOCKERS` / `SCOPE-MISMATCH` verdict applies, mergeable is
trivially `false` — no need to re-check the four sub-conditions.

### Section placement and content

Append a new `## Mergeable decision` section to the review draft
**after** the verdict-specific body (findings / blockers / scope
narrative) and **before** the closing `<!-- sgai-prs: ai-cycle -->`
marker. The section MUST start with the binary verdict on its own
line:

```markdown
## Mergeable decision

**MERGEABLE** — <one-line reason>
```

OR

```markdown
## Mergeable decision

**NEEDS-WORK** — <one-line reason>
```

Translate the heading and the inline reason into `triage.lang`.
The binary token (`MERGEABLE` / `NEEDS-WORK`) stays in English
regardless — it is a status token, not prose.

#### When `MERGEABLE`

Close with a short **rationale paragraph** (2–5 sentences)
explaining:

- Why the PR is a good addition (what it improves / fixes /
  clarifies).
- Why the findings, if any, are quality nudges that do NOT block
  merge — they can be folded into a follow-up PR or addressed by
  the maintainer post-merge.

The rationale's tone matches the rest of the draft: technical,
direct, no fluff, no @-mentions. It is the AI review pass's
explicit endorsement of the merge path — the maintainer reads it
and decides.

#### When `NEEDS-WORK`

Close with a **`Path to merge` block** listing the concrete
actions the author must complete before the PR is mergeable. Use
a bulleted list, one action per bullet. Each action MUST be:

- **Concrete** — name the file, the line, the open point ID, the
  blocker ID, the convention reference. The author should not
  have to re-read the analysis to know what to do.
- **Resolvable** — name the acceptable resolution. For open points
  specifically, the resolution is one of three paths:
  - **(a)** Commit the resolution directly into `context/` (or
    the relevant diffed file), removing the TBD marker.
  - **(b)** Move the open point to an ADR under
    `.project/decisions/` (when the resolution is an
    architectural decision worth recording).
  - **(c)** Reference a follow-up PR or GitHub issue tracking the
    open point (when resolution is out of scope for this PR but
    the author commits to handling it elsewhere).

Template:

```markdown
### Path to merge

- **[OP-1]** Resolve the open point on `<file>:<line>` ("<short
  TBD quote>"). Options: (a) commit the resolution to
  `context/<file>`, (b) move to a new ADR under
  `.project/decisions/`, or (c) reference a follow-up issue.
- **[F2.3]** Fix the broken cross-reference at `<file>:<line>` —
  the link to `<target>` does not resolve.
- **[F1.2]** Provide the source for the claim "<verbatim>" — the
  AI review pass could not verify it against `context/` or DASH
  6th. Either cite the canonical source in the PR body, or
  rephrase the claim to remove the unverifiable specificity.
- **[B1]** Address blocker: <one-line summary>. See blockers
  section above for the full reasoning.
```

After the bullets, add a one-line closer:

> *Once these are addressed, the AI review pass expects the PR
> to flip to MERGEABLE on the next cycle.*

(Translated into `triage.lang`.)

## Routing (D8)

Decide whether the review is posted as a top-level comment (`gh pr
comment`) or as a formal `--comment` review (`gh pr review
--comment`, which may include inline line-anchored comments).

Read the `## Aggregate` section of `analyze.md` to get
`line_specific_findings`. Then:

| Verdict | line_specific_findings | Routing |
|---|---|---|
| `LGTM` | 0 | `comment` |
| `LGTM` | ≥ 1 | `review` |
| `SUGGESTIONS` | 0 | `comment` |
| `SUGGESTIONS` | ≥ 1 | `review` (hybrid: inline + summary) |
| `BLOCKERS` | any | `review` (formal, registered as a review) |
| `SCOPE-MISMATCH` | any | `review` (formal, registered as a review) |

The `review` routing for blockers / scope-mismatch is intentional:
formal `gh pr review --comment` shows up in the PR's "Reviews"
section, not just inline with the comment thread — Nicolas sees
at a glance the AI raised a review (without it counting as approve
/ request-changes per D12).

## Hard guard against approve / request-changes (D12)

The verdict and routing produced by this prompt MUST NEVER
correspond to `gh pr review --approve` or
`gh pr review --request-changes`. The pipeline only posts:

- `gh pr comment <N> --body-file ...` (when routing = `comment`),
  or
- `gh pr review <N> --comment --body-file ...` (when routing =
  `review`), optionally accompanied by inline comments via the
  Pulls API (see `post-review.prompt`).

If you find yourself drafting language that asks for approval or
explicit change requests at the GitHub-review-state level (vs.
asking the author to revise), STOP and reframe — the pipeline does
not have permission to gate merges. It only contributes review
comments. Nicolas merges by hand.

## Output language

The draft MUST be written in the language stored as `lang` in the
triage verdict (D4 fallback: `en`). All headings, prose, code
comments inside fenced blocks, and the closing line stay in the
detected language. Technical terms (`OverlayPresentation`,
`ListMPD`, `DASH 6th`, `SCTE-35`, `ReplacePresentation`,
`status=update`, etc.) are kept verbatim regardless of the
language — they are proper nouns of the spec.

## Mandatory marker

Every review draft, regardless of verdict or routing, MUST end
with the following hidden HTML comment on its own final line:

```html
<!-- sgai-prs: ai-cycle -->
```

This marker is what `detect-prs.prompt` uses to count AI cycles
for the anti-loop cap (D5). The marker is invisible in GitHub's
rendered view but readable when the body is fetched via the API.

When routing is `review` + the review carries inline comments, the
marker MUST live in the **summary body** (the one passed to
`gh pr review --comment --body-file`). The inline comments do NOT
carry the marker — see `detect-prs.prompt §"Inline review comments
are not counted"`.

## Severity-driven disclaimer (D3)

If `triage.severity == "requirements"` OR
`triage.severity == "architectural"`, the draft MUST open with
this exact disclaimer line (translated into `triage.lang`):

- **`en`**: *"This review was auto-drafted by the project's AI
  agent — please cross-check with project owner before relying on
  it."*
- **`es`**: *"Esta revisión fue auto-redactada por el agente AI
  del proyecto — por favor, cruzar referencias con el dueño del
  proyecto antes de basarse en ella."*
- **`pt`**: *"Esta revisão foi rascunhada automaticamente pelo
  agente IA do projeto — por favor, valide com o dono do projeto
  antes de confiar nela."*
- **`fr`**: *"Cette revue a été rédigée automatiquement par
  l'agent IA du projet — merci de vérifier auprès du responsable
  du projet avant de vous y fier."*
- **`it`**: *"Questa revisione è stata redatta automaticamente
  dall'agente IA del progetto — vi preghiamo di verificare con il
  proprietario del progetto prima di affidarvi a essa."*
- **`de`**: *"Diese Review wurde automatisch vom KI-Agenten des
  Projekts entworfen — bitte vor der Verwendung mit dem
  Projektverantwortlichen abgleichen."*

Format the disclaimer as a blockquote (`> …`) so it stands out
visually.

For `severity ∈ {cosmetic, spec-detail}` the disclaimer is NOT
added — those reviews don't carry decision weight, and front-
loading a disclaimer on every minor reply would dilute its signal.

## Cycle-aware tone

`cycle_count == 1` is the default case: the AI is reviewing the PR
for the first time. No special framing.

When `cycle_count > 1`, the author has pushed new commits and/or
replied to a prior AI review, and the pipeline is preparing a
follow-up. The draft MUST:

1. Open with a brief acknowledgement of the prior cycle. Example
   phrasings (in the detected language; English here):
   - "Thanks for the follow-up — to the new points raised:"
   - "Re-reviewing after the latest push: addressing the new
     diff below."
   The acknowledgement is one sentence at most; do NOT recap what
   was said before — the author and the maintainer can scroll up.
2. Focus the body on the **new** material — the latest commits
   and the author's reply. Do NOT re-litigate findings that were
   already settled in `cycle-<C-1>/analyze.md` unless the new diff
   reintroduces them.
3. Keep the severity-driven disclaimer (D3) and the closing marker
   `<!-- sgai-prs: ai-cycle -->` exactly as on cycle 1. The marker
   is what `detect-prs` counts on the next run.
4. **Mergeable decision continuity**: when `cycle_count > 1` AND
   the prior cycle's decision was `mergeable: false`, the response
   MUST explicitly state whether the author's new commits flipped
   the decision to `mergeable: true` (and why — which OPs got
   resolved, which blockers got fixed), OR kept it `mergeable:
   false` (and which OPs / blockers remain unresolved). This is
   the load-bearing info for the author — without it they cannot
   tell if they need to keep iterating. State this near the top of
   the body, ideally right after the acknowledgement of point 1.

## Verdict-specific draft shape

Each shape below describes the **verdict-specific body** that
precedes the mandatory `## Mergeable decision` section. The
"close" bullet in each shape is the lead-in to the mergeable
section — keep it short, do NOT duplicate the rationale or the
`Path to merge` block (those live in the mergeable section).

### `LGTM`

Goal: confirm the PR is clean and signal the author the review
pass found no blockers.

Structure:

1. **Acknowledge** what the PR does (one sentence, lift from
   `triage.claim_summary`).
2. **Confirm** the four axes were checked and came back clean (or
   only `info`). One short bullet per axis is enough:
   - Content: verified against `context/...` / DASH 6th §X (if
     grounded).
   - Convention: no `CLAUDE.md` violations.
   - Scope: title / body / diff coherent.
   - Downstream: <stale artefacts to rebuild after merge, or "no
     downstream effects">.
3. **Close** with a brief "no blockers found from the AI review
   pass; awaiting human merge decision". Explicitly NOT an
   approval (D12).

### `SUGGESTIONS`

Goal: surface the non-bloquant findings, organised so they are
easy to triage.

Structure:

1. **Acknowledge** what the PR does (one sentence).
2. **Note** the review found no blockers; the items below are
   suggestions / info only.
3. **List the findings** grouped by axis. For each finding:
   - Use the `[F1.1]` IDs from `analyze.md` so the reviewer can
     cross-reference.
   - When `granularity == line-specific`, include the
     `path:line` ref inline in the draft body. The same finding
     will also appear as an inline comment if routing is
     `review` (post-review handles the inline emission).
   - Quote the verbatim evidence briefly.
4. **Close** with a brief "the suggestions are quality nudges; the
   PR can merge as-is from the AI review pass's standpoint".

### `BLOCKERS`

Goal: surface the blockers explicitly, with reasoning, and
recommend the author revise before the maintainer merges.

Structure:

1. **Acknowledge** what the PR is trying to do.
2. **State the headline**: this AI review pass identified
   `<n>` blocker(s) that warrant revision before merge. Frame this
   as a recommendation to the maintainer, NOT as a formal change-
   request (D12).
3. **List the blockers** in order of severity, each with:
   - The `[FX.Y]` ID.
   - One-paragraph explanation of why it is a blocker (not a
     suggestion) — usually: "this contradicts canonical source
     X", "this breaks convention Y which CLAUDE.md describes as
     'MUST NOT'", or "this would break the layering arrow".
   - The verbatim evidence + citation.
   - When line-specific, the `path:line` ref.
4. **List any suggestions** (lower severity) underneath, so they
   are not lost.
5. **Close** with a brief "blockers raised for the maintainer's
   review; no automatic gating applied". The author may push fixes
   and a follow-up cycle will be triggered (subject to the D5 cap).

### `SCOPE-MISMATCH`

Goal: surface that the PR's body / title and its actual diff
disagree on **what** the PR is, and recommend a structural fix
(split / retitle / rewrite the body).

Structure:

1. **Acknowledge** what the PR says it does (lift from
   `triage.claim_summary`) AND what the diff actually does (lift
   from the scope-axis findings).
2. **State the headline**: the AI review pass found a scope
   mismatch that should be resolved before merge — either by
   splitting the PR, retitling, or rewriting the body to match
   the diff.
3. **Walk through the scope findings** with verbatim evidence
   ("body says X, diff actually does Y").
4. **List any other findings** (content / convention /
   downstream) underneath — they may still apply but are
   secondary to the scope issue.
5. **Close** with a concrete recommendation: split, retitle, or
   rewrite the body. Frame as a recommendation, not a directive
   (D12).

## Machine-readable metadata header

Above the visible draft body, write a hidden HTML comment with the
fields `post-review.prompt` needs to route without re-parsing the
analysis. The block MUST be exactly this shape (white-space
tolerated, but the keys are stable):

```html
<!-- sgai-prs-meta:
verdict: <LGTM | SUGGESTIONS | BLOCKERS | SCOPE-MISMATCH>
routing: <comment | review>
line_specific_findings: <integer>
severity: <cosmetic | spec-detail | requirements | architectural>
lang: <en | es | pt | fr | it | de>
cycle: <C>
mergeable: <true | false>
mergeable_reason: <short text — see below>
-->
```

`mergeable` is a boolean (`true` / `false`) per the "Mergeable
decision" section above.

`mergeable_reason` is a short text token (one line, no embedded
newlines, no quotes) describing **why** the decision went the way
it did. Use a controlled vocabulary so `post-review.prompt` can
log it consistently:

- When `mergeable: true`:
  - `pristine` — `LGTM`, no findings at all.
  - `clean-with-suggestions` — `SUGGESTIONS`, all suggestions
    optional, no open points, no broken refs.
  - `info-only` — only `info` findings (e.g. downstream-stale
    notes already acknowledged by the author).
- When `mergeable: false`:
  - `open-points` — at least one open point TBD remains
    unresolved.
  - `unverifiable-claims` — at least one load-bearing claim could
    not be grounded.
  - `broken-refs` — at least one internal cross-ref does not
    resolve.
  - `blockers` — verdict is `BLOCKERS`.
  - `scope-mismatch` — verdict is `SCOPE-MISMATCH`.
  - `multiple` — more than one of the above applies; the visible
    body breaks down which.

This block lives at the very top of the file, before the
disclaimer / body. It is not visible when the body is rendered on
GitHub (HTML comments are stripped from the rendered output) but
it is readable when the file is read from disk by
`post-review.prompt`.

## Output format

Write `output-github-prs/pr-<N>/cycle-<C>/review.md` exactly as it
should appear when posted, with the machine-readable header on top.

Concretely:

```markdown
<!-- sgai-prs-meta:
verdict: SUGGESTIONS
routing: review
line_specific_findings: 2
severity: requirements
lang: en
cycle: 1
mergeable: false
mergeable_reason: open-points
-->

> <disclaimer line if severity ∈ {requirements, architectural}>

<verdict-appropriate body — see structures above>

## Mergeable decision

**NEEDS-WORK** — <one-line reason>

<rationale paragraph if MERGEABLE, OR `### Path to merge` block
if NEEDS-WORK — see "Mergeable decision" section above>

<!-- sgai-prs: ai-cycle -->
```

Aim for **concise, decision-friendly drafts**: 250–500 words for
most reviews. Longer is fine for `BLOCKERS` / `SCOPE-MISMATCH` /
`requirements` / `architectural` PRs that warrant more careful
framing, but resist padding — the review is the start of a
conversation, not a position paper. Match the style guidance in
`../CLAUDE.md §"Tone for the spec and generated artefacts"`:
technical, direct, no fluff.

## Critical do-NOTs

- Do NOT use the verbs "approve" / "approved" / "approving" in any
  draft language that could be read as a GitHub-state approval.
  The AI does not approve PRs (D12). Phrase clean reviews as "no
  blockers found from the AI review pass" — not "looks good to
  me, approving".
- Do NOT use the verbs "request changes" / "block merge" in any
  draft language that could be read as a GitHub-state change-
  request. Phrase blockers as "the AI pass identified the following
  blockers — recommending revision before merge".
- Do NOT claim a finding is verified against an external standard
  unless NotebookLM grounding produced the citation (or the spec
  itself is the source). When in doubt, tag the finding with
  `[inferred]` and lower the severity.
- Do NOT invent ADR IDs, requirement IDs, or use case IDs. If you
  reference one, verify it exists in `.project/decisions/` or
  `context/`.
- Do NOT translate proper nouns of the spec.
- Do NOT @-mention anyone. The draft addresses the PR publicly;
  pings are for human follow-ups, not auto-drafts.
- Do NOT include the inline comment bodies in the summary draft
  when routing is `review` + line-specific findings — those bodies
  are emitted separately by `post-review.prompt` via the Pulls
  API. The summary should reference the line-specific findings
  generically (e.g. "see the inline comment on `<path>:<line>`")
  to avoid double-posting the same text.
